{"ts":"2026-06-27T03:28:47.334Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Identifying Mock Data**\n\nI've just realized the central data model is loaded with a plethora of mock lists. Specifically, I'm seeing lists for client accounts, users, projects, agent operations, and agent health data. This is a bit unexpected and requires further investigation to understand its purpose and implications within the system.\n\n\n**Mapping Data Previews**\n\nI'm now cataloging all the data previews, specifically focusing on `previewDocuments`, `previewInvoices`, `previewSupportTickets`, and so on. My goal is to map these previews to the listed application pages, which are projects, documents, billing, and support. I'm also confirming what data UI components we already have. It looks like `data-tables.tsx` exists.\n\n\n**Evaluating Component Reusability**\n\nI'm now diving into the existing components. The simple `DataTable` and `filter-bar.tsx` are my focus. I'm assessing their details and potential for premium enhancement, aiming for a unified, reusable set across the private app. I need to ensure these components meet the specifications for the listed pages, supporting all necessary filters and states, while still offering a bespoke feel. The goal is to maximize component reusability and adhere to the project requirements.\n\n\n**Designing Table Components**\n\nI'm now outlining the design for the HTML tables. My vision is a high-end, glassmorphic dark-theme console, aligning with the AI theme and using subtle cyan and ruby-red accents. Row hovers and sticky headers will provide user-friendliness, while responsive cards will improve mobile views. No backend calls are planned, and crisp text using mono fonts for numbers and hashes will ensure clarity.\n\n\n**Defining UI Component Details**\n\nI'm now detailing the planned user interface components. I envision a gorgeous layered sidebar drawer that slides out from the right on row selection. For filtering, I plan a search bar with a glowing prefix icon, clear button, and shortcut badge. Multiple dropdown filters for status, type, and date range will be included, alongside sort controls and a local visible count badge. The custom table will feature a sticky header with uppercase, monospaced headers and sort indicators. Interactive rows will include hover effects and a status-color left border. Mobile views will have elegant card fallbacks.\n\n\n"}}
